Yes, it can! 

In modern Angular, especially with standalone components, a component can inport a directive directly

Example:

@Component({
  selector: 'app-user-card',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [HighlightDirective],
  templateUrl: './user-card.component.html',
})
export class UserCardComponent {}

Then the directive can be used inside that component’s template.

- I use ngOnChanges when a component needs to react to changes coming from an @Input().

- It is useful when the parent component passes new data and the child component needs to update something based on that change.

- Example cases:
  - reload data when an input ID changes
  - recalculate values when input data changes
  - update charts, filters, or forms based on new input
  - compare previous and current input values

- It solves the problem of keeping a child component synchronized with data changes from the parent.

- I prefer ngOnChanges when the logic depends specifically on @Input() changes, instead of putting that logic randomly in the template or ngOnInit.


Example

export class UserComponent implements OnChanges {
  @Input() userId!: number;

  ngOnChanges(changes: SimpleChanges): void {
    if (changes['userId']) {
      console.log('User ID changed:', this.userId);

      // reload user data here
      this.loadUser(this.userId);
    }
  }

  loadUser(id: number): void {
    // API call example
  }
}
